# Clayworth Surface: Δ(2,3,12) on G₂(2)

The Clayworth graph is a cubic arc-transitive graph on 4032 vertices,
`Sab(G₂(2), C₃)`, embedded on a surface of genus 505 via the triangle
group Δ(2,3,12). The face rotation R (order 12) and vertex rotation S
(order 3) satisfy `(RS)² = 1` and generate G₂(2) (order 12096).

* V = 4032 = |G₂(2)|/3, E = 6048 = |G₂(2)|/2, F = 1008 = |G₂(2)|/12
* χ = 4032 − 6048 + 1008 = −1008 = 2 − 2 × 505
* Tiling: {12,3} — 1008 dodecagonal faces on a genus 505 surface
* CSS code: [[6048, 1010, ≥ 12]]

The data (R, S as permutations of 12096 darts, plus coset maps) was
computed by GAP and verified: all triangle group relations hold, all
face boundaries visit distinct edges, and all edges connect distinct vertices.

## References

* Robin Langer, *Symmetric Graphs and their Quotients*, arXiv:1306.4798
